2025-06-21 14:23:52,084 - INFO - full_response_text: That's an excerpt from the paper's abstract.  The OCR has some errors because of the formatting and font.  Here's a corrected version:

"**Abstract**—Stereo matching algorithms are nearly always designed to find matches between a single pair of images. A method is presented that was specifically designed to operate on sequences of images. This method considers the cost of matching image points in both the spatial and temporal domain. To maintain real-time operation, a temporal cost aggregation method is used to evaluate the likelihood of matches that is invariant with respect to the number of prior images being considered. This method has been implemented on"


The abstract summarizes the paper's main contribution: a novel stereo matching algorithm designed for video sequences (not just single image pairs) that's both fast (real-time) and accurate, using a clever temporal cost aggregation technique.

